Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the
noodles.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped) into small pieces.

Trim the @green beans{80%g}(trimmed and cut into thirds) and cut into thirds.

When boiling, add the @egg noodle nests{2} and green beans to the water and cook
until tender, ~{4%minutes}.

Once the noodles and green beans are cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and run under
cold water to stop the noodles sticking together.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Add the onion to the pan and stir-fry until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Stir in the garlic and @Chinese five spice{1%sachet} and fry until fragrant, ~{1%minute} more.

Once fragrant, stir through the @Szechuan paste{1%sachet}, @soy sauce{25%ml},
@rice vinegar{15%ml}, @tomato ketchup{2%tbsp}, @honey{1%tbsp} and @water{125%ml}.

Simmer until thickened slightly, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Drain the @king prawns{300%g}, then stir them into the sauce and cook for another
~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. They're
> cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Once the prawns are cooked, stir through the noodles and green beans. Toss to
coat in the sauce and simmer until piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}. Add a splash of
water if you feel it needs it.

Share the prawn noodles between your serving bowls.

Sprinkle over the @chilli flakes{pinch} to finish (add less if you'd prefer
things milder).

Enjoy!